'''Flight mode''' is a function in some electronic devices (notably [[mobile phones]]) that deactivates [[radio transmitters]] and receivers such that the phone's secondary features (such as its music and [[java games|games]]) can be used in places such as [[passenger jet|planes]] and [[clinic]]s.

Flight mode (or [[airplane mode]]) mostly applies to cell phones, but it also applicable to any electronic device that transmits radio signals as its primary function.
The term is something of a minomer, however, since a cell phone cannot be legally used as a cell phone on public flights.  As a practical matter most cell phone users simply treat flight mode as a power-saving feature or a soft-off.

The [[Sony Ericsson W800]] mobile phone was first to introduce this feature on its [[Walkman]]-brand phone; since then other brands have followed suit.
